{"type":"message","id":"d0e17904","parentId":"7505bdd6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T09:43:49.961Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me check the OpenClaw config to see how exec tool works and if I can make rtk wrap commands automatically. Looking at the OpenClaw docs might help, but the simplest approach would be to add aliases for common commands to use rtk by default.\n\nActually, the real question is whether OpenClaw's exec tool calls commands through bash. If so, adding aliases in .bashrc could help. But it won't help for commands that are explicitly called like `python3 -c ...` or complex commands.\n\nAnother approach: I could add a wrapper script or use a bashrc function that automatically intercepts commands. But that would be complex.\n\nActually, looking at the rtk skill, for OpenClaw it says:\n> ⚠️ For OpenClaw agents: hooks don't auto-apply. Use rtk <cmd> explicitly (see below).\n\nSo OpenClaw doesn't support auto-hooks like Claude Code. The only way to make it truly automatic would be to modify the shell environment to intercept commands, but that would be unreliable for complex commands with pipes, redirects, etc.\n\nThe best I can do practically is:\n1. Add aliases for common commands (git, ls, find, etc.)\n2. Ensure my exec commands always use rtk prefix\n3. Document that this is a manual process for OpenClaw\n\nLet me add aliases to bashrc for common commands.\n","thinkingSignature":"1492a21fbcb4f542e3b785ff7431c41a85425962cac7ac0b811c6eed0b076233"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_z1s2i9vo5gru_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat >> ~/.bashrc << 'EOF'\n\n# RTK aliases — auto-rewrite common commands for token savings\nalias git='rtk git'\nalias ls='rtk ls'\nalias find='rtk find'\nalias grep='rtk grep'\nalias diff='rtk diff'\nalias cat='rtk read'\nalias tree='rtk tree'\nEOF\necho \"Added RTK aliases to ~/.bashrc\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"i