{"type":"message","id":"991c2451","parentId":"da4042f1","timestamp":"2026-05-10T09:47:24.885Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to make RTK work automatically in OpenClaw's exec tool. They want it fixed so that every command goes through RTK without me having to manually prefix it. They don't trust AI to remember to do it manually.\n\nLet me think about the real solution. The issue is:\n1. OpenClaw exec calls binaries directly (not through shell)\n2. Aliases in bashrc don't work for direct binary calls\n3. RTK hook is designed for Claude Code, not OpenClaw\n\nThe real solution for OpenClaw would be to create wrapper scripts that replace the standard commands. For example, create `/usr/local/bin/git` that wraps `rtk git`, then ensure this is in PATH before the normal git.\n\n\nSo I'd need to create wrapper scripts for each command like git, ls, find, and grep, place them in a directory that comes first in PATH, make them executable, and then update OpenClaw's shell configuration to use that directory.\n\nActually, I'm realizing OpenClaw already has an exec tool that might support shell interpretation if I just prepend \"rtk \" to the commands, so the simplest approach would be to configure that directly without needing wrapper scripts. /bin/bash -c \"rtk git status\"` instead of `git status`\n2. This would require modifying how exec tool is configured\n\nThe most reliable fix for OpenClaw exec would be to create a wrapper that intercepts commands. But this is complex.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. The exec tool in OpenClaw - can I configure it to prepend \"rtk\" to commands automatically?\n\nOr alternatively, I could create a custom shell script that replaces the standard utilities, and modify OpenClaw to use that shell as its shell.\n\nLet me try creating wrapper scripts in a custom path, then modifying the PATH or shell configuration OpenClaw uses.\n\nLet me create a `/home/apinan/.local/bin/` wrapper directory and put rtk-wrapped versions of common commands there, then ensure this comes first in PATH. For OpenClaw exec, I need to figure out if it respects PATH order or calls binaries directly. If it uses bash, I can set aliases via BASH_ENV or change the shell OpenClaw uses. But if it calls binaries directly, the wrappers in PATH won't help since the binary name wouldn't match.\n\nActually, the simplest solution might be to create actual binary wrappers in `/usr/local/bin/` that replace commands like `ls`, `find`, `grep`, and `git` with shell scripts that invoke their rtk equivalents. This way, when OpenClaw calls these standard utilities, they're already pointing to the rtk-enhanced versions.\n\nLet me start by creating these wrappers in `/home/apinan/.local/bin/` and see if OpenClaw's exec tool picks them up through the PATH.\n","thinkingSignature":"6f0456712d23f11805befad8f1163e96f67039372b6a8e2fd49e38ffdf8ce1e0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_psadphq8dtwv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p ~/.local/bin && export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n\n# Create rtk-wrapped wrappers for common commands\nfor cmd in git ls find grep diff tree; do\ncat > ~/.local/bin/$cmd << EOF\n#!/bin/bash\nexec rtk $cmd \"\\$@\"\nEOF\nchmod +x ~/.local/bin/$cmd\ndone\n\n# Also create cat wrapper\ncat > ~/.local/bin/cat << EOF\n#!/bin/bash\nexec rtk read \"\\$@\"\nEOF\nchmod +x ~/.local/bin/cat\n\necho \"Created wrappers:\"\nls -la ~/.local/bin/"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":456,"output":734,"cacheRead":63104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":64294,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778406414965,"responseId":"064f8710fb9657a596c11c8a2a72f48a"}}
